        <p class="mb-4">
          Our <strong>perpetual safe withdrawal rate calculator</strong> is the most precise free tool for determining how much you can spend forever while preserving your portfolio&#8217;s purchasing power. Whether you are a <strong>FatFIRE retiree</strong> wanting to ensure generational wealth, an <strong>estate planner</strong> designing a multi-generational trust, or a <strong>foundation manager</strong> with a perpetual spending mandate, this calculator gives you the mathematically correct answer using the Fisher Equation rather than simplified approximations.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Why Choose a Perpetual Safe Withdrawal Rate?</h3>

        <p class="mb-4">
          The traditional retirement planning question is "how much can I spend without running out before I die?" The perpetual wealth question is different: <strong>"how much can I spend and still leave my heirs the same purchasing power I started with?"</strong> The difference is profound. The 4% rule was designed for a 30-year retirement and explicitly assumes principal depletion. A perpetual SWR is designed for infinite time horizons — it is the withdrawal rate that would keep the Harvard endowment operating forever.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          The <strong>opportunity cost of using the wrong withdrawal rate</strong> cuts both ways. If you use the 4% rule for a perpetual portfolio, you slowly deplete wealth meant to span generations. If you use a perpetual SWR for a personal retirement, you leave a large unspent balance that you could have enjoyed. The key is matching the withdrawal strategy to your actual goal. This calculator is specifically designed for the <strong>perpetual goal</strong> — wealth that lasts forever.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          For <strong>high-net-worth individuals</strong> and <strong>generational wealth planners</strong>, the perpetual SWR provides a clear upper bound on safe spending. Even if you ultimately choose a higher withdrawal rate, understanding your perpetual SWR gives you the baseline from which all less-conservative strategies deviate. It is the foundation of any responsible withdrawal plan with a multi-generational time horizon.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Key Features of This Perpetual SWR Calculator</h3>

        <p class="mb-4">
          The calculator uses the <strong>exact Fisher Equation</strong> rather than the simplified (and inaccurate) "nominal minus inflation" approximation. This matters — at higher inflation rates, the Fisher Equation gives significantly different results than the approximation. The <strong>real vs. nominal projection chart</strong> visualizes the Inflation Illusion over 50–100 years, showing the flat red line (real purchasing power) alongside the exponentially growing blue line (nominal balance) so you can truly understand how perpetual withdrawals work.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          Adjust the <strong>investment fee slider</strong> from 0% to 3% to see the dramatic impact of costs on your safe spend — every 0.5% in fees reduces your annual withdrawal by $10,000 on a $2M portfolio. The <strong>time horizon slider</strong> lets you project from 50 to 100 years, and the <strong>unsustainable warning</strong> alerts you when the combination of returns, inflation, and fees makes perpetual withdrawals impossible. All calculations are performed client-side — no data is sent to any server, and nothing is stored. The chart automatically updates when you switch between dark and light mode.
        </p>
      </div>
